After writing nearly a hundred short stories, O'Donnell moved on to writing novels, and

00:54.600 --> 00:55.880
so far he's written six.

00:56.380 --> 01:01.220
These include Bandersnatch, Mayflies, War of Emission, and the Journeys of McGill Fian

01:01.220 --> 01:03.580
series, Caverns, Rees, and Lava.

01:04.120 --> 01:07.980
O'Donnell spent a good deal of time in Korea before and after college, and he majored in

01:07.980 --> 01:09.120
Chinese Studies at college.

01:09.520 --> 01:11.920
We asked him if having lived in the Orient influences his writing.

03:11.920 --> 03:13.920
Mayflies is O'Donnell's second novel.

03:14.160 --> 03:18.140
It's the story of a generation ship conveying thousands of settlers to a far destination.

03:18.580 --> 03:20.940
But the focus is on the computer that guides the ship.

03:21.340 --> 03:25.060
You see its core is a living human brain that has retained the memories of the time it was

03:25.060 --> 03:26.880
in the body of Dr. Gerard Medeclura.

03:27.260 --> 03:29.460
O'Donnell explains the genesis of this concept.

03:30.400 --> 03:36.620
Mayflies started all this, actually it was a workshop exercise.

03:37.100 --> 03:46.060
I was at the time in a workshop here in New Haven, and we had to do, oh I forget, a two-paragraph

03:46.060 --> 03:47.980
description of someone.

03:49.300 --> 03:58.280
And I described this character, Medeclura, who took more than the two paragraphs to describe

03:58.280 --> 03:58.560
the character.

03:58.560 --> 04:01.100
And I began on for about a page, and all of a sudden he died.

04:03.340 --> 04:07.380
And I took it into the workshop, and people said, well yes, those are nice paragraphs

04:07.380 --> 04:10.740
and very good description, but boy what have you done here?

04:11.120 --> 04:12.860
You've created a character and then killed him.

04:13.100 --> 04:13.460
What a waste.

04:14.040 --> 04:17.720
I got angry and said, well, you know, maybe I killed him, but it's not a waste.

04:18.620 --> 04:20.160
But I can make something of him.

04:21.160 --> 04:22.780
And they said, we dare you.

04:23.180 --> 04:28.040
And pretty soon Mayflies was underway with me trying to prove you could write a book about

04:28.040 --> 04:29.800
a protagonist who died on page one.

04:31.240 --> 04:36.060
And have that protagonist a very vital part of the entire story, rather than just a haunting

04:36.060 --> 04:36.540
memory.

04:37.440 --> 04:44.220
The only way to do that was of course to somehow keep him alive and one thing led to another.

04:44.460 --> 04:49.220
And the next thing I knew, Medeclura was a central computer on the Good Shit Night

04:49.220 --> 04:49.500
Flower.

