06:29.800 --> 06:33.820
Bandersnatch, Science Fiction author Kevin O'Donnell Jr.'s first novel, made his paperback

06:33.820 --> 06:35.140
appearance in 1979.

06:36.240 --> 06:40.480
The first half of Bandersnatch depicts a 22nd century America deeply divided between the

06:40.480 --> 06:41.300
haves and the have-nots.

06:41.800 --> 06:44.060
A burgeoning bureaucracy strangles the have-nots.

06:44.280 --> 06:48.900
In five of O'Donnell's novels, the protagonist must contend with stultifying bureaucracies.

06:48.900 --> 06:52.980
When we ask O'Donnell if this represents a personal view, this is what he told us.

07:20.020 --> 07:24.980
It achieves a goal beyond its stated purpose, or it acquires a new goal.

07:25.860 --> 07:33.900
And that goal is to survive, to perpetuate itself, to expand, to get fat and strong and

07:33.900 --> 07:34.780
secure.

07:36.860 --> 07:41.620
It goes all the way back to Parkinson's Law, and the work expands until the time available

07:41.620 --> 07:43.420
and when it has, you hire two assistants.

07:46.020 --> 07:53.420
I think this is an inevitable trend in any bureaucracy, whether it's Western-style capitalism

07:53.940 --> 07:58.840
or Maoist communism.

07:59.360 --> 08:01.670
One of Mao's big campaigns was against bureaucracy.

08:02.640 --> 08:08.900
He was constantly railing against the way that no matter what he said, no matter what he did,

08:09.380 --> 08:11.100
the bureaucracy kept growing.

08:11.100 --> 08:18.440
It kept issuing new regulations and new rules, and here he was, the most powerful man in China,

08:18.600 --> 08:20.000
and he couldn't affect bureaucracy.

08:21.040 --> 08:23.920
So yeah, that's a very personal sort of point.

08:24.800 --> 08:28.040
A primitive planet is a setting for the second half of Bandersnatch.

08:28.220 --> 08:32.960
In a climactic struggle, the protagonist, also known as Bandersnatch, kills a monstrous,

08:33.080 --> 08:34.800
bear-like alien which has attacked him.

08:35.140 --> 08:39.220
Then he discovers the alien has a young cub which for some reason befriends him and becomes

08:39.220 --> 08:39.980
his sidekick.

08:39.980 --> 08:43.560
Well, Donald told us that the appearance and character of the cub were unplanned,

08:43.600 --> 08:44.620
had just sprang into being.

08:45.280 --> 08:49.900
A baby bear actually came about almost entirely by accident.

08:51.680 --> 08:58.540
I had had, you know, Bandersnatch wandering through this alien jungle.

09:01.900 --> 09:05.280
And I realized he needed like a...

09:05.280 --> 09:14.940
The way the story was going, he had to have this climactic battle sequence with a natural

09:14.940 --> 09:17.760
force, some sort of wild animal.

09:18.460 --> 09:24.320
And I hadn't had any wild animals, and they're really big enough for him.

09:27.340 --> 09:34.540
All of a sudden, off the page came this monstrous, bear-like animal that almost loomed up before him

09:34.540 --> 09:36.860
and started attacking him.

09:37.280 --> 09:39.340
And, well, he won.

09:39.840 --> 09:43.200
And there I was with a dead bear on the ground.

09:43.640 --> 09:49.680
And just sort of somehow my fingers kept going and there was a sound from the distance

09:49.680 --> 09:50.720
and it was the cub.

09:51.060 --> 09:55.120
And the next thing I knew, he had a sidekick as you put it.

09:55.860 --> 09:58.880
That was just accidental, really.

10:00.060 --> 10:02.420
Sidekicks are common in science fiction and fantasy.

10:02.420 --> 10:04.900
Here are Donald comments on the role of a sidekick.

10:05.460 --> 10:09.840
I think it helps when the protagonist has a sidekick of some sort.

10:13.140 --> 10:18.600
When you're writing science fiction, well, you know, why not give the hero an alien sidekick,

10:19.080 --> 10:20.660
Sam and the McGill fiend series?

10:22.360 --> 10:28.460
I think it lets you do a little exploring into alien psychology,

10:28.460 --> 10:37.760
and at the same time, it lets you keep making sort of mirror-like observations of human culture.

