12:16.020 --> 12:19.740
Kevin O'Donnell Jr. science fiction novel War of Omissions, published in 1982.

12:20.280 --> 12:25.120
In the book, O'Donnell describes a violent revolution which takes place in late 20th century America.

12:25.500 --> 12:27.060
This revolution begins in the northeast.

12:27.780 --> 12:31.660
O'Donnell presents the thoughts and actions of the participants on both sides of the revolution.

12:32.120 --> 12:34.320
We asked him what he was trying to get across in War of Omission.

12:35.480 --> 12:40.700
The modern-day recapitulation of the statements of power corrupt,

12:41.200 --> 12:43.200
and absolute power corrupt, absolutely.

12:47.020 --> 12:54.180
I was trying to say, hey, it's real easy to say that the system stinks and we'll wipe it out.

12:54.180 --> 12:55.960
But what happens when you do wipe it out?

12:58.740 --> 13:06.420
You know, I think this is where every revolutionary since, you know, the French in 1787 is screwed up thoroughly.

13:07.100 --> 13:12.720
They say, well, you know, the present system is corrupt and it's bloated and it stinks and let's throw it out and we'll have paradise.

13:14.120 --> 13:15.600
I think that's stupid.

13:16.620 --> 13:18.400
I'm not a defender of the system.

13:18.400 --> 13:29.400
But I think the sort of sweeping, burn it down just doesn't work because, you know, you wind up building on rubble.

13:29.660 --> 13:34.060
You don't move into a structure that you can clean up and straighten out.

13:34.900 --> 13:36.000
You've got ashes.

13:37.000 --> 13:41.120
And I think really those two things were what the book was all about.

13:41.820 --> 13:47.120
The science-fictional element in War of Omission is the Tissere, a weapon the revolutionaries perfect

13:47.120 --> 13:50.340
which wipes out all objects in the target area instantaneously.

13:50.800 --> 13:52.120
It makes these objects disappear.

13:52.760 --> 13:54.380
Right, but it does something else as well.

13:54.800 --> 13:57.440
It wipes out the memory of the target area from everyone's minds.

13:58.120 --> 14:02.920
So if a person's house and family were deleted by a Tissere, neither he nor anyone else would have any memory of them.

14:03.100 --> 14:08.440
Most of the action, especially Tissere deletions, takes place in New Haven, the city where O'Donnell now lives.

14:09.200 --> 14:12.400
We asked O'Donnell if he enjoyed writing scenes in which New Haven gets destroyed.

14:12.780 --> 14:14.440
That generated an interesting sidelight.

14:14.440 --> 14:24.960
I was sort of offended by my publisher that they cut some references in there.

14:25.420 --> 14:26.860
We have a building here in town.

14:27.200 --> 14:33.880
It's the Knights of Columbus building and I think it's possibly the ugliest structure ever erected anywhere in America.

14:33.880 --> 14:46.920
It's a huge, towering, ugly brick building with massive turrets at each of the four corners of the building.

14:47.480 --> 14:54.780
It looks like it was designed to hold off an attack by mad and archers.

14:57.020 --> 15:00.060
I took great pleasure in destroying that in the book.

15:00.880 --> 15:03.560
Having it totally obliterated from the face of the earth.

15:04.060 --> 15:08.040
At one point I had a character bring it back and change his mind. It was so ugly.

15:08.920 --> 15:11.960
But the editor cut it right out.

15:12.460 --> 15:13.580
No, sorry, I can't do that.

15:15.120 --> 15:17.380
But it was fun taking out the rest in New Haven.

15:18.100 --> 15:20.940
The concept of the Tissere is the heart of War of Omission.

15:20.940 --> 15:24.300
Donal told us he put a lot of effort to make the Tissere believable.

15:24.860 --> 15:27.680
The hardest part was trying to make it plausible.

15:30.120 --> 15:37.080
A reviewer who has appeared that has really faulted the book on those grounds.

15:38.400 --> 15:42.320
For whatever reason that person did not believe the Tissere.

15:43.900 --> 15:48.620
I put so much effort into trying to make it believable.

15:48.620 --> 15:52.680
I think I put more effort into that than any other part of the book.

15:53.660 --> 15:55.440
Trying to make it seem very natural.

15:55.840 --> 15:59.340
And trying to provide possible explanations for why this happened.

16:00.540 --> 16:04.000
Sort of brief meditations on the nature of reality.

16:05.920 --> 16:13.700
For those who accepted the explanation, who believed the Tissere, I think the book worked.

16:13.700 --> 16:17.880
And I think if you can't believe that the book just falls flat.

16:18.620 --> 16:21.260
The Tissere is believable and War of Omission works.

